<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n22069e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n22" href="#n22069e">N22 (VI.B.17)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n22all.htm#n22069e"> 69(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">C</font> not use blotting paper</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Among his <font color="green">[Biggar&apos;s]</font> personal traits was a strong aversion for giving any opportunity for his signature being copied; and, when he wrote a letter at the House, he allowed it to dry without at any time using blotting-paper. He carried this idea so far that when, as he very frequently did, he signed an order of admission for strangers, he could always be seen waving it in the air as he went through the Lobby and corridor, so that the signature might be naturally dried. <small> Sir Alfred Robbins, <a name="TL5Y" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#TL5Y"><cite title="source">Parnell: The Last Five Years</cite></a> (1926) 128</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c11063i" href="c11all.htm#c11063i">VI.C.11:063(i)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
